üîπ Option 1 ‚Äî Recommended (ISO Install)

This is the official way.

Download the ISO
From Security Onion Download
.
Example: SecurityOnion-2.4.180.iso (version may change).

Create boot media / VM

If physical: burn ISO to USB.

If VM: attach ISO as CD/DVD and boot.

Boot & Install

At boot menu: choose Install Security Onion.

Go through installer (similar to Ubuntu Server): set hostname, disk, user.

Initial Setup (so-setup)
After reboot, run:

sudo so-setup


Choose Standalone (lab) or Distributed (production).

Pick the interface for packet capture.

Set the admin password.

Access Web Interface
Open browser ‚Üí https://<server-ip>
Login with admin / password you set.
From here you‚Äôll see SOC UI, Kibana, Hunt, TheHive, etc.

üîπ Option 2 ‚Äî Advanced (on top of Ubuntu 24.04)

This is not recommended for beginners, but possible if you want to layer it on an existing Ubuntu.

Update System

sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y


Add Security Onion Repo

curl -s https://securityonionsolutions.com/keys/securityonion.gpg | sudo apt-key add -
echo "deb [arch=amd64] https://repo.securityonion.net/ focal main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/securityonion.list
sudo apt update


Install Security Onion Packages

sudo apt install securityonion -y


Run Setup

sudo so-setup


‚ö†Ô∏è But keep in mind: Security Onion devs strongly recommend using the ISO installer, because it ensures kernel, Suricata, Zeek, and dependencies are correctly tuned.

